datastructures.trees

Interface BinarySearchTree<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - The Comparable type held by the BinarySearchTree.
    All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>, Tree<T>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AVLBinarySearchTree, LinkedBinarySearchTree, RedBlackBinarySearchTree

    public interface BinarySearchTree<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>
extends Tree<T>
    A BinarySearchTree is a Tree with a maximum of 2 children nodes per node which allows for adding and removing nodes in a sorted manner. As such, it will extend the Tree interface but it will also restrict the objects it stores to Comparable ones. There are only going to be two new methods in this interface: add(T) and remove(T). Following classical semantics, for every given node, elements in the left subtree of the node are smaller (as defined by their compareTo() definitions) than the element at the node, which is subsequently smaller than or equal to the nodes in the right subtree. Note that this interface does not allow for methods that balance it. For BinarySearchTrees that allow for auto-balancing, AVL trees or Red-Black trees should be used.
    Since:
    October 2013
    Author:
    Jason Filippou (jasonfil@cs.umd.edu)
